# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: motor-drive-electronics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A **motor controller** is a device or group of devices that can coordinate in a predetermined manner the performance of an electric motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A motor controller might include a manual or automatic means for starting and stopping the motor, selecting forward or reverse rotation, selecting and regulating the speed, regulating or limiting the torque, and protecting against overloads and electrical faults.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Motor controllers may use electromechanical switching, or may use power electronics devices to regulate the speed and direction of a motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Motor controllers are used with both DC motors (direct current) and AC motors (alternating current).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A controller includes means to connect the motor's windings to the electrical power supply, and may also include overload, over-current, and overheating protection and wiring (i.e. magnetic starter).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A motor controller may also supervise the motor's field circuit, or detect conditions such as low supply voltage, incorrect polarity or incorrect phase sequence, or high motor temperature.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Some motor controllers limit the inrush starting current, allowing the motor to accelerate itself and connected mechanical load more slowly than a direct connection.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Motor controllers may be manual, requiring an operator to sequence a starting switch through steps to accelerate the load, or may be fully automatic, using internal timers or current sensors to accelerate the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Some types of motor controllers also allow adjustment of the speed of the electric motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] For direct-current motors, the controller may adjust the voltage applied to the motor, or adjust the current flowing in the motor's field winding.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The physical design and packaging of motor controllers is about as varied as that of electric motors themselves.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A wall-mounted toggle switch with suitable ratings may be all that is needed for a household ventilation fan.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Power tools and household appliances may have a trigger switch that only turns the motor on and off.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Industrial motors may be more complex controllers connected to automation systems; a factory may have a large number of motor controllers grouped in a motor control center.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Controllers for electric travelling cranes or electric vehicles may be mounted on the mobile equipment.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The largest motor controllers are used with the pumping motors of pumped storage hydroelectric plants, and may carry ratings of tens of thousands of horsepower (kilowatts).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Motor controllers can be manually, remotely or automatically operated.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] They may include only the means for starting and stopping the motor or they may include other functions.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Electric motors can be powered by AC or DC power sources.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] There are many type of AC and DC motors - namely brush, brushless, servo and stepper motors - depending on their mechanical construction.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A motor controller is connected to a power source, such as a battery pack or power supply, and control circuitry in the form of analog or digital input signals.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A small motor can be started by simply connecting it to power.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A larger motor requires a specialized switching unit called a motor starter or motor contactor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] When energized, a direct on line (DOL) starter immediately connects the motor terminals directly to the power supply.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In smaller sizes a motor starter is a manually operated switch; larger motors, or those requiring remote or automatic control, use magnetic contactors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Very large motors running on medium voltage power supplies (thousands of volts) may use power circuit breakers as switching elements.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A **direct on line** (DOL) or *across the line* starter applies the full line voltage to the motor terminals.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This is the simplest type of motor starter.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A DOL motor starter often contains protection devices (see below), and in some cases, condition monitoring.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Smaller sizes of direct on-line starters are manually operated; larger sizes use an electromechanical contactor to switch the motor circuit.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Solid-state direct on line starters also exist.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A direct on line starter can be used if the high inrush current of the motor does not cause excessive voltage drop in the supply circuit.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The maximum size of a motor allowed on a direct on line starter may be limited by the supply utility for this reason.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] For example, a utility may require rural customers to use reduced-voltage starters for motors larger than 10 kW.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] DOL starting is sometimes used to start small water pumps, compressors, fans and conveyor belts.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In the case of an asynchronous motor, such as the 3-phase squirrel-cage motor, the motor will draw a high starting current until it has run up to full speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This starting current is typically 6-7 times greater than the full load current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] To reduce the inrush current, larger motors will have reduced-voltage starters or adjustable-speed drives in order to minimise voltage dips to the power supply.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A reversing starter can connect the motor for rotation in either direction.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Such a starter contains two DOL circuits — one for clockwise operation and the other for counter-clockwise operation, with mechanical and electrical interlocks to prevent simultaneous closure.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] For three phase motors, this is achieved by swapping the wires connecting any two phases.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Single phase AC motors and direct-current motors often can be reversed by swapping two wires but this is not always the case.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Motor starters other than 'DOL' connect the motor through a resistance to reduce the voltage the motor coils get on start up.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The resistance for this needs to be sized to the motor - and a quick source for a good resistance to use is another coil in the motor - i.e. series/parallel.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In series gives a gentler start then switched to parallel for full power running.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] When this is done with three phase motors, it is commonly called a star-delta (US: Y-delta) starter.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Old star-delta starters were manually operated and often incorporated an ammeter so the person operating the starter could see when the motor was up to speed by the fact the current it was drawing had stopped decreasing.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] More modern starters have built-in timers to switch from star to delta and are set by the electrical installer of the machine.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The machine's operator simply presses a green button once and the rest of the start procedure is automated.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A typical starter includes protection against overload, both electrical and mechanical, and protection against 'random' starting - if, for instance, the power has been off and has just come back on.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] An acronym for this type of protection is TONVR - Thermal Overload, No Volt Release.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] It insists that the green button is pressed to start the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The green button switches on a solenoid which closes a contactor (i.e. switch) to primarily power the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] It also powers the solenoid to keep the power turned on when the green button is released.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In a power failure, the contactor opens turning itself and the motor off.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The only way the motor can then be started is by pressing the green button.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The contactor can be quickly tripped by the starter passing a very high current due to an electrical fault downstream of it in either the wiring to the motor or within the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The thermal overload protection consists of a heating element on each power wire which heats a bimetallic strip.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The hotter the strip, the more it deflects to the point it pushes a trip bar which disconnects power to the contactor solenoid, turning everything off.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Thermal overloads come in different range ratings and this should be chosen to match the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Within the range, they are adjustable enabling the installer to set it correctly for the given motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] DOL gives a quick start so is used more commonly with generally smaller motors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] It is also used on machines with an uneven load such as piston type compressors where the full power of the motor is needed to get the piston past the compression stage - the actual working stage.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Star-delta is generally used with larger motors or where either the motor is under no load at starting, very little load or a consistent load.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] It is particularly suited to motors driving machinery with heavy flywheels - to get the flywheels up to speed before the machine is engaged and driven by the flywheel.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Reduced-voltage or soft starters connect the motor to the power supply through a voltage reduction device and increases the applied voltage gradually or in steps.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Two or more contactors may be used to provide reduced voltage starting of a motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] By using an autotransformer or a series inductance, a lower voltage is present at the motor terminals, reducing starting torque and inrush current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Once the motor has come up to some fraction of its full-load speed, the starter switches to full voltage at the motor terminals.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Since the autotransformer or series reactor only carries the heavy motor starting current for a few seconds, the devices can be much smaller compared to continuously rated equipment.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The transition between reduced and full voltage may be based on elapsed time, or triggered when a current sensor shows the motor current has begun to reduce.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] An autotransformer starter was patented in 1908.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Larger 3 phase induction motors can have their power reduced within the motor !
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The motor is started 'DOL' with full voltage supplied to the field coils of the motor outer part ('stator').
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The inner part ('rotor') has a current induced into it to once again react with the magnetic field generated by the stator.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] By breaking the rotor into parts and electrically connecting these parts to external resistances via slip rings and brushes as well as control contactors, the magnetic power of the rotor can be varied - i.e. reduced, for starting or low power running.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Although a much more complex process, it means the currents (electrical loads) being switched are significantly lower than if reducing the power to the main feed of the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A third way to achieve a very smooth progressive start is to dip resistance rods into a conductive liquid (e.g. mercury) which has a layer of insulative oil on the top.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] As the rods are lowered the resistance is gradually reduced.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A star delta starter is another type of Reduced-voltage starter in induction motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A star delta starter will start a motor with a star connected stator winding.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] When motor reaches about 80% of its full load speed, it will begin to run in a delta connected stator winding.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] (1) Manual Operated Star Delta Starter, (2) Automatic Star Delta.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The manual operated star delta starter mainly consists of a TPDT switch which stands for Triple Pole Double Throw switch.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This switch changes stator winding from star to delta.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] During starting condition stator winding is connected in the form of a star.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Now we shall see how a star delta starter reduces the starting current of a three-phase induction motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The above function achieved by using a power contactor and timer in automatic star delta starter.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The automatic star delta starter is manufactured from three contactors, a timer and a thermal overload.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The contactors are smaller than the single contactor used in a direct on line starter as they are controlling winding currents only.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The currents through the winding are 1/root 3 (58%) of the current in the line.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] There are two contactors that are close during run, often referred to as the main contractor and the delta contactor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] These are AC3 rated at 58% of the current rating of the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The third contactor is the star contactor and that only carries star current while the motor is connected in star.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The current in star is one third of the current in delta, so this contactor can be AC3 rated at one third (33%) of the motor rating.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The transition from star to delta can be an open transition or a closed transition.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] During open transition, the motor starter momentarily disconnects from the motor and reconnects in a delta configuration.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In closed transition, the transition from the star to delta configuration is achieved without disconnecting the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In order to achieve that, an additional three-pole contactor and three resistors are required.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] An *adjustable-speed drive* (ASD) or *variable-speed drive* (VSD) is an interconnected combination of equipment that provides a means of driving and adjusting the operating speed of a mechanical load.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] An electrical adjustable-speed drive consists of an electric motor and a speed controller or power converter plus auxiliary devices and equipment.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In common usage, the term "drive" is often applied to just the controller.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Most modern ASDs and VSDs can also implement soft motor starting.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] An *Intelligent Motor Controller* (IMC) uses a microprocessor to control power electronic devices used for motor control.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] IMCs monitor the load on a motor and accordingly match motor torque to motor load.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This is accomplished by reducing the voltage to the AC terminals and at the same time lowering current and kvar.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This can provide a measure of energy efficiency improvement for motors that run under light load for a large part of the time, resulting in less heat, noise, and vibrations generated by the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A starter will contain protective devices for the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] At a minimum this would include a thermal overload relay.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The thermal overload is designed to open the starting circuit and thus cut the power to the motor in the event of the motor drawing too much current from the supply for an extended time.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The overload relay has a normally closed contact which opens due to heat generated by excessive current flowing through the circuit.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Thermal overloads have a small heating device that increases in temperature as the motor running current increases.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] There are two types of thermal overload relay.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] In one type, a bimetallic strip located close to a heater deflects as the heater temperature rises until it mechanically causes the device to trip and open the circuit, cutting power to the motor should it become overloaded.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A thermal overload will accommodate the brief high starting current of a motor while accurately protecting it from a running current overload.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The heater coil and the action of the bi-metallic strip introduce a time delay that affords the motor time to start and settle into normal running current without the thermal overload tripping.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Thermal overloads can be manually or automatically resettable depending on their application and have an adjuster that allows them to be accurately set to the motor run current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A second type of thermal overload relay uses a eutectic alloy, like a solder, to retain a spring-loaded contact.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] When too much current passes through the heating element for too long a time, the alloy melts and the spring releases the contact, opening the control circuit and shutting down the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Since eutectic alloy elements are not adjustable, they are resistant to casual tampering but require changing the heater coil element to match the motor rated current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Electronic digital overload relays containing a microprocessor may also be used, especially for high-value motors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] These devices model the heating of the motor windings by monitoring the motor current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] They can also include metering and communication functions.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Starters using magnetic contactors usually derive the power supply for the contactor coil from the same source as the motor supply.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] An auxiliary contact from the contactor is used to maintain the contactor coil energized after the start command for the motor has been released.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] If a momentary loss of supply voltage occurs, the contactor will open and not close again until a new start command is given.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This prevents restarting of the motor after a power failure.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This connection also provides a small degree of protection against low power supply voltage and loss of a phase.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] However, since contactor coils will hold the circuit closed with as little as 80% of normal voltage applied to the coil, this is not a primary means of protecting motors from low voltage operation.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Some devices can be added so that during a voltage drop, the device maintains the current flow that is sufficient for the hold-in coil to keep the contacts closed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The circuit is designed allows current for the hold-in coil for voltage sags down to 15-25% voltage.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] After the electrical power has been restored (typically after a time delay of 30 to 60 seconds), then the time sequences of the automatic restarts of multiple motors are set to automatically begin.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Without a time sequenced schedule, any attempt to restart many motors simultaneously could lead to partial or total site wide power failure.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Servo controllers are a wide category of motor control.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Servo controllers use position feedback to close the control loop.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] This is commonly implemented with position encoders, resolvers, and Hall effect sensors to directly measure the rotor's position.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Other position feedback methods measure the back EMF in the undriven coils to infer the rotor position, or detect the Kick-Back voltage transient (spike) that is generated whenever the power to a coil is instantaneously switched off.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] These are therefore often called "sensorless" control methods.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A servo may be controlled using pulse-width modulation (PWM).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] How long the pulse remains high (typically between 1 and 2 milliseconds) determines where the motor will try to position itself.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Another control method is pulse and direction.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] A stepper, or stepping, motor is a synchronous, brushless, high pole count, polyphase motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Control is usually, but not exclusively, done open loop, *i.e.*, the rotor position is assumed to follow a controlled rotating field.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Because of this, precise positioning with steppers is simpler and cheaper than closed loop controls.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] Modern stepper controllers drive the motor with much higher voltages than the motor nameplate rated voltage, and limit current through chopping.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/motor-controller] The usual setup is to have a positioning controller, known as an *indexer*, sending step and direction pulses to a separate higher voltage drive circuit which is responsible for commutation and current limiting.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] A three-phase inverter as shown to the right converts a DC supply, via a series of switches, to three output legs which could be connected to a three-phase motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] The switches must be controlled so that at no time are both switches in the same leg turned on or else the DC supply would be shorted.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] This requirement may be met by the complementary operation of the switches within a leg. i.e. if A+ is on then A− is off and vice versa.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] This leads to eight possible switching vectors for the inverter, V0 through V7 with six active switching vectors and two zero vectors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] Note that looking down the columns for the active switching vectors V1-6, the output voltages vary as a pulsed sinusoid, with each leg offset by 120 degrees of phase angle.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] To implement space vector modulation, a reference signal Vref is sampled with a frequency fs (Ts = 1/fs).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] The reference signal may be generated from three separate phase references using the αβγ transform.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] The reference vector is then synthesized using a combination of the two adjacent active switching vectors and one or both of the zero vectors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] Various strategies of selecting the order of the vectors and which zero vector(s) to use exist.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] Strategy selection will affect the harmonic content and the switching losses.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] More complicated SVM strategies for the unbalanced operation of four-leg three-phase inverters do exist.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] In these strategies the switching vectors define a 3D shape (a hexagonal prism in $\alpha \beta \gamma$ coordinates or a dodecahedron in abc coordinates) rather than a 2D hexagon.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/space-vector-modulation] General SVM techniques are also available for converters with any number of legs and levels.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Depending on its topology, it controls the associated voltage or current variation.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] VFDs are used in applications ranging from small appliances to large compressors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Systems using VFDs can be more efficient than hydraulic systems, such as in systems with pumps and damper control for fans.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Since the 1980s, power electronics technology has reduced VFD cost and size and has improved performance through advances in semiconductor switching devices, drive topologies, simulation and control techniques, and control hardware and software.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] VFDs include low- and medium-voltage AC–AC and DC–AC topologies.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Pulse-width modulation (PWM) variable-frequency drive projects started in the 1960s at Strömberg in Finland.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Martti Harmoinen is regarded as the inventor of this technology.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Strömberg managed to sell the idea of PWM drive to Helsinki Metro in 1973 and in 1982 the first PWM drive SAMI10 were operational.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A variable-frequency drive is a device used in a drive system consisting of the following three main sub-systems: AC motor, main drive controller assembly, and drive/operator interface.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The AC electric motor used in a VFD system is usually a three-phase induction motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Some types of single-phase motors or synchronous motors can be advantageous in some situations, but generally three-phase induction motors are preferred as the most economical.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Motors that are designed for fixed-speed operation are often used.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Elevated-voltage stresses imposed on induction motors that are supplied by VFDs require that such motors be designed for definite-purpose inverter-fed duty in accordance with such requirements as Part 31 of NEMA Standard MG-1.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The VFD controller is a solid-state power electronics conversion system consisting of three distinct sub-systems: a rectifier bridge converter, a direct current (DC) link, and an inverter.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Voltage-source inverter (VSI) drives (see 'Generic topologies' sub-section below) are by far the most common type of drives.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Most drives are AC–AC drives in that they convert AC line input to AC inverter output.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] However, in some applications such as common DC bus or solar applications, drives are configured as DC–AC drives.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The most basic rectifier converter for the VSI drive is configured as a three-phase, six-pulse, full-wave diode bridge.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In a VSI drive, the DC link consists of a capacitor which smooths out the converter's DC output ripple and provides a stiff input to the inverter.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This filtered DC voltage is converted to quasi-sinusoidal AC voltage output using the inverter's active switching elements.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] VSI drives provide higher power factor and lower harmonic distortion than phase-controlled current-source inverter (CSI) and load-commutated inverter (LCI) drives (see 'Generic topologies' sub-section below).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The drive controller can also be configured as a phase converter having single-phase converter input and three-phase inverter output.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Controller advances have exploited dramatic increases in the voltage and current ratings and switching frequency of solid-state power devices over the past six decades.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Introduced in 1983, the insulated-gate bipolar transistor (IGBT) has in the past two decades come to dominate VFDs as an inverter switching device.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In variable-torque applications suited for Volts-per-Hertz (V/Hz) drive control, AC motor characteristics require that the voltage magnitude of the inverter's output to the motor be adjusted to match the required load torque in a linear V/Hz relationship.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] For example, for 460 V, 60 Hz motors, this linear V/Hz relationship is 460/60 = 7.67 V/Hz.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] While suitable in wide-ranging applications, V/Hz control is sub-optimal in high-performance applications involving low speed or demanding, dynamic speed regulation, positioning, and reversing load requirements.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Some V/Hz control drives can also operate in quadratic V/Hz mode or can even be programmed to suit special multi-point V/Hz paths.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The two other drive control platforms, vector control and direct torque control (DTC), adjust the motor voltage magnitude, angle from reference, and frequency so as to precisely control the motor's magnetic flux and mechanical torque.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Although space vector pulse-width modulation (SVPWM) is becoming increasingly popular, sinusoidal PWM (SPWM) is the most straightforward method used to vary drives' motor voltage (or current) and frequency.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] 1), quasi-sinusoidal, variable-pulse-width output is constructed from intersections of a saw-toothed carrier signal with a modulating sinusoidal signal which is variable in operating frequency as well as in voltage (or current).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Operation of the motors above rated nameplate speed (base speed) is possible, but is limited to conditions that do not require more power than the nameplate rating of the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This is sometimes called "field weakening" and, for AC motors, means operating at less than rated V/Hz and above rated nameplate speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Permanent magnet synchronous motors have quite limited field-weakening speed range due to the constant magnet flux linkage.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Wound-rotor synchronous motors and induction motors have much wider speed range.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] At higher speeds, the induction motor torque has to be limited further due to the lowering of the breakaway torque of the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Thus, rated power can be typically produced only up to 130–150% of the rated nameplate speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Wound-rotor synchronous motors can be run at even higher speeds.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In rolling mill drives, often 200–300% of the base speed is used.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The mechanical strength of the rotor limits the maximum speed of the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] An embedded microprocessor governs the overall operation of the VFD controller.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Basic programming of the microprocessor is provided as user-inaccessible firmware.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] User programming of display, variable, and function block parameters is provided to control, protect, and monitor the VFD, motor, and driven equipment.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The operator interface provides a means for an operator to start and stop the motor and adjust the operating speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The VFD may also be controlled by a programmable logic controller through Modbus or another similar interface.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Additional operator control functions might include reversing, and switching between manual speed adjustment and automatic control from an external process control signal.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The operator interface often includes an alphanumeric display or indication lights and meters to provide information about the operation of the drive.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] An operator interface keypad and display unit is often provided on the front of the VFD controller as shown in the photograph above.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The keypad display can often be cable-connected and mounted a short distance from the VFD controller.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Most are also provided with input and output (I/O) terminals for connecting push buttons, switches, and other operator interface devices or control signals.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A serial communications port is also often available to allow the VFD to be configured, adjusted, monitored, and controlled using a computer.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] There are two main ways to control the speed of a VFD; networked or hardwired.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Networked involves transmitting the intended speed over a communication protocol such as Modbus, Modbus/TCP, EtherNet/IP, or via a keypad using Display Serial Interface while hardwired involves a pure electrical means of communication.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Typical means of hardwired communication are: 4-20mA, 0-10VDC, or using the internal 24VDC power supply with a potentiometer.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Speed control can be performed either remotely or locally, depending on the application's requirements.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Remote control instructs the VFD to ignore speed commands from the keypad while local control instructs the VFD to ignore external control and only abide by the keypad.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Depending on the model a VFD's operating parameters can be programmed via: dedicated programming software, internal keypad, external keypad, or SD card.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] VFDs will often block out most programming changes while running.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Typical parameters that need to be set include: motor nameplate information, speed reference source, on/off control source and braking control.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] It is also common for VFDs to provide debugging information such as fault codes and the states of the input signals.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Most VFDs allow auto-starting, which will drive the output to a designated frequency after a power cycle, after a fault has been cleared, or after the emergency stop signal has been restored (generally emergency stops are active low logic).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] One popular way to control a VFD is to enable auto-start and place L1, L2, and L3 into a contactor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Powering on the contactor thus turns on the drive and has it output to a designated speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Depending on the sophistication of the drive multiple auto-starting behavior can be developed e.g. the drive auto-starts on power up but does not auto-start from clearing an emergency stop until a reset has been cycled.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Most applications involve single-quadrant loads operating in quadrant I, such as in variable-torque (e.g. centrifugal pumps or fans) and certain constant-torque (e.g. extruders) loads.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Certain applications involve two-quadrant loads operating in quadrant I and II where the speed is positive but the torque changes polarity as in case of a fan decelerating faster than natural mechanical losses.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Some sources define two-quadrant drives as loads operating in quadrants I and III where the speed and torque is same (positive or negative) polarity in both directions.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Certain high-performance applications involve four-quadrant loads (Quadrants I to IV) where the speed and torque can be in any direction such as in hoists, elevators, and hilly conveyors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Regeneration can occur only in the drive's DC link bus when inverter voltage is smaller in magnitude than the motor back-EMF and inverter voltage and back-EMF are the same polarity.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In starting a motor, a VFD initially applies a low frequency and voltage, thus avoiding high inrush-current associated with direct-on-line starting.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] After the start of the VFD, the applied frequency and voltage are increased at a controlled rate or ramped up to accelerate the load.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This starting method typically allows a motor to develop 150% of its rated torque while the VFD is drawing less than 50% of its rated current from the mains in the low-speed range.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A VFD can be adjusted to produce a steady 150% starting torque from standstill right up to full speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] However, motor cooling deteriorates and can result in overheating as speed decreases such that prolonged low-speed operation with significant torque is not usually possible without separately motorized fan ventilation.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] With a VFD, the stopping sequence is just the opposite as the starting sequence.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The frequency and voltage applied to the motor are ramped down at a controlled rate.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] When the frequency approaches zero, the motor is shut off.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A small amount of braking torque is available to help decelerate the load a little faster than it would stop if the motor were simply switched off and allowed to coast.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Additional braking torque can be obtained by adding a braking circuit (resistor controlled by a transistor) to dissipate the braking energy.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] With a four-quadrant rectifier (active front-end), the VFD is able to brake the load by applying a reverse torque and injecting the energy back to the AC line.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Many fixed-speed motor load applications that are supplied direct from AC line power can save energy when they are operated at variable speed by means of VFD.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Such energy cost savings are especially pronounced in variable-torque centrifugal fan and pump applications, where the load's torque and power vary with the square and cube, respectively, of the speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This change gives a large power reduction compared to fixed-speed operation for a relatively small reduction in speed.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] For example, at 63% speed a motor load consumes only 25% of its full-speed power.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This reduction is in accordance with affinity laws that define the relationship between various centrifugal load variables.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In the United States, an estimated 60–65% of electrical energy is used to supply motors, 75% of which are variable-torque fan, pump, and compressor loads.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Eighteen percent of the energy used in the 40 million motors in the U.S. could be saved by efficient energy improvement technologies such as VFDs.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Only about 3% of the total installed base of AC motors are provided with AC drives.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] However, it is estimated that drive technology is adopted in as many as 30–40% of all newly installed motors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] AC drives are used to bring about process and quality improvements in industrial and commercial applications' acceleration, flow, monitoring, pressure, speed, temperature, tension, and torque.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Fixed-speed loads subject the motor to a high starting torque and to current surges that are up to eight times the full-load current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] AC drives instead gradually ramp the motor up to operating speed to lessen mechanical and electrical stress, reducing maintenance and repair costs, and extending the life of the motor and the driven equipment.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Variable-speed drives can also run a motor in specialized patterns to further minimize mechanical and electrical stress.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] For example, an S-curve pattern can be applied to a conveyor application for smoother deceleration and acceleration control, which reduces the backlash that can occur when a conveyor is accelerating or decelerating.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Performance factors tending to favor the use of DC drives over AC drives include such requirements as continuous operation at low speed, four-quadrant operation with regeneration, frequent acceleration and deceleration routines, and need for the motor to be protected for a hazardous area.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] VFDs are available with voltage and current ratings covering a wide range of single-phase and multi-phase AC motors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Low-voltage (LV) drives are designed to operate at output voltages equal to or less than 690 V.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] While motor-application LV drives are available in ratings of up to the order of 5 or 6 MW, economic considerations typically favor medium-voltage (MV) drives with much lower power ratings.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In some applications a step-up transformer is placed between a LV drive and a MV motor load.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] MV drives are typically rated for motor applications greater than between about 375 and 750 kW (503 and 1,006 hp).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] MV drives have historically required considerably more application design effort than required for LV drive applications.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The power rating of MV drives can reach 100 MW (130,000 hp), a range of different drive topologies being involved for different rating, performance, power quality, and reliability requirements.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] When the VFD loads are relatively small in comparison to the large, stiff power system available from the electric power company, the effects of VFD harmonic distortion of the AC grid can often be within acceptable limits.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Furthermore, in low-voltage networks, harmonics caused by single-phase equipment such as computers and TVs are partially cancelled by three-phase diode bridge harmonics because their 5th and 7th harmonics are in counterphase.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] When the power company's voltage becomes distorted due to harmonics, losses in other loads such as normal fixed-speed AC motors are increased.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This condition may lead to overheating and shorter operating life.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Also, substation transformers and compensation capacitors are affected negatively.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In particular, capacitors can cause resonance conditions that can unacceptably magnify harmonic levels.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] To limit the voltage distortion, owners of VFD load may be required to install filtering equipment to reduce harmonic distortion below acceptable limits.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Alternatively, the utility may adopt a solution by installing filtering equipment of its own at substations affected by the large amount of VFD equipment being used.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In high-power installations, harmonic distortion can be reduced by supplying multi-pulse rectifier-bridge VFDs from transformers with multiple phase-shifted windings.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] It is also possible to replace the standard diode-bridge rectifier with a bi-directional IGBT switching device bridge mirroring the standard inverter which uses IGBT switching device output to the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Such rectifiers are referred to by various designations including active infeed converter (AIC), active rectifier, IGBT supply unit (ISU), active front end (AFE), or four-quadrant operation.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] With PWM control and a suitable input reactor, an AFE's AC line current waveform can be nearly sinusoidal.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] AFE inherently regenerates energy in four-quadrant mode from the DC side to the AC grid.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Thus, no braking resistor is needed, and the efficiency of the drive is improved if the drive is frequently required to brake the motor.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Two other harmonics mitigation techniques exploit use of passive or active filters connected to a common bus with at least one VFD branch load on the bus.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Passive filters involve the design of one or more low-pass LC filter traps, each trap being tuned as required to a harmonic frequency (5th, 7th, 11th, 13th, . . . kq±1, where k=integer, q=pulse number of converter).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] It is very common practice for power companies or their customers to impose harmonic distortion limits based on IEC or IEEE standards.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] For example, IEEE Standard 519 limits at the customer's connection point call for the maximum individual frequency voltage harmonic to be no more than 3% of the fundamental and call for the voltage total harmonic distortion (THD) to be no more than 5% for a general AC power supply system.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] One drive uses a default switching frequency setting of 4 kHz.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Reducing the drive's switching frequency (the carrier-frequency) reduces the heat generated by the IGBTs.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A carrier frequency of at least ten times the desired output frequency is used to establish the PWM switching intervals.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A carrier frequency in the range of 2,000 to 16,000 Hz is common for LV [low voltage, under 600 Volts AC] VFDs.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A higher carrier frequency produces a better sine wave approximation but incurs higher switching losses in the IGBT, decreasing the overall power conversion efficiency.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Some drives have a noise smoothing feature that can be turned on to introduce a random variation to the switching frequency.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This distributes the acoustic noise over a range of frequencies to lower the peak noise intensity.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The carrier-frequency pulsed output voltage of a PWM VFD causes rapid rise times in these pulses, the transmission line effects of which must be considered.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Since the transmission-line impedance of the cable and motor are different, pulses tend to reflect back from the motor terminals into the cable.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The resulting reflections can produce overvoltages equal to twice the DC bus voltage or up to 3.1 times the rated line voltage for long cable runs, putting high stress on the cable and motor windings, and eventual insulation failure.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Insulation standards for three-phase motors rated 230 V or less adequately protect against such long-lead overvoltages.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] On 460 V or 575 V systems and inverters with 3rd-generation 0.1-microsecond-rise-time IGBTs, the maximum recommended cable distance between VFD and motor is about 50 m or 150 feet.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] For emerging SiC MOSFET powered drives, significant overvoltages have been observed at cable lengths as short as 3 meters.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Selection of optimum PWM carrier frequency for AC drives involves balancing noise, heat, motor insulation stress, common-mode voltage-induced motor bearing current damage, smooth motor operation, and other factors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Further harmonics attenuation can be obtained by using an LCR low-pass sine wave filter or dV/dt filter.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Carrier frequencies above 5 kHz are likely to cause bearing damage unless protective measures are taken.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] PWM drives are inherently associated with high-frequency common-mode voltages and currents which may cause trouble with motor bearings.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] When these high-frequency voltages find a path to earth through a bearing, transfer of metal or electrical discharge machining (EDM) sparking occurs between the bearing's ball and the bearing's race.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Over time, EDM-based sparking causes erosion in the bearing race that can be seen as a fluting pattern.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] In large motors, the stray capacitance of the windings provides paths for high-frequency currents that pass through the motor shaft ends, leading to a circulating type of bearing current.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Poor grounding of motor stators can lead to shaft-to-ground bearing currents.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Small motors with poorly grounded driven equipment are susceptible to high-frequency bearing currents.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Prevention of high-frequency bearing current damage uses three approaches: good cabling and grounding practices, interruption of bearing currents, and filtering or damping of common-mode currents through common mode chokes.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Good cabling and grounding practices can include use of shielded, symmetrical-geometry power cable to supply the motor, installation of shaft grounding brushes, and conductive bearing grease.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Bearing currents can be interrupted by installation of insulated bearings and specially designed electrostatic-shielded induction motors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Filtering and damping high-frequency bearing can be done though inserting soft magnetic cores over the three phases giving a high frequency impedance against the common mode or motor bearing currents.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Another approach is to use instead of standard 2-level inverter drives, using either 3-level inverter drives or matrix converters.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Torque generated by the drive causes the induction motor to run at synchronous speed less the slip.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] If the load drives the motor faster than synchronous speed, the motor acts as a generator, converting mechanical power back to electrical power.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] This power is returned to the drive's DC link element (capacitor or reactor).
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] A DC-link-connected electronic power switch or braking DC chopper controls dissipation of this power as heat in a set of resistors.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Cooling fans may be used to prevent resistor overheating.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Dynamic braking wastes braking energy by transforming it to heat.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] By contrast, regenerative drives recover braking energy by injecting this energy into the AC line.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] The capital cost of regenerative drives is, however, relatively high.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Regenerative AC drives have the capacity to recover the braking energy of a load moving faster than the designated motor speed (an *overhauling* load) and return it to the power system.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Cycloconverter, Scherbius, matrix, CSI, and LCI drives inherently allow return of energy from the load to the line, while voltage-source inverters require an additional converter to return energy to the supply.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Regeneration is useful in VFDs only where the value of the recovered energy is large compared to the extra cost of a regenerative system, and if the system requires frequent braking and starting.
[src:motor-drive-electronics/variable-frequency-drive] Regenerative VFDs are widely used where speed control of overhauling loads is required.
